taller (when present) |\n| File path | `C:\\Users\\<user>\\AppData\\Local\\Temp\\rarsfx0\\setup.exe` | High | WinRAR SFX wrapper dropped by `k.exe` |\n| File name | `perfmon-kr.exe`, `perfmon-kvw.exe`, `perfmon-khk.dll`, `perfmon-ki.dll`, `perfmon-kwb.dll`, `pkl.bin`, `opt.dat`, `web.dt` | High | PKL component set |\n| String | `BlazingTools Perfect Keylogger` (ASCII or UTF-16LE) | High | Plaintext family marker |\n| SHA-256 | `fc7f5094bc182a05e782e0b775eccab9e662a3d207e89ab7f075db18a4c19c75` | High | `perfmon-kr.exe` |\n| SHA-256 | `128cdb7c58bfda11a88c21e41e48df47f2122a1761d69aec5af79e241a712185` | High | `perfmon-kvw.exe` |\n| SHA-256 | `225efff946151edeb6f860f5e4d68aa7025ca7abef67ddb215f5c89445d3356c` | High | `perfmon-khk.dll` |\n| SHA-256 | `fa76d9059fc4fe103e3de1868c76d86efbac9295fcd3e5f1c430cd1c5b4ad710` | High | `perfmon-ki.dll` |\n| SHA-256 | `8db5e3bdd57ed77f80e1dbd5f11a48a19f69faa2281f1039b615ee8b4a09407c` | High | `perfmon-kwb.dll` |\n| SHA-256 | `5f7925d5e11232a4391daabd56559ad79e662d03e9d6f791b4ace3ec3142a78b` | High | `pkl.bin` (data DB) |\n| SHA-256 | `4b64135662977d806f8d12067815848827cd977c3696a60c30d85a157f6b945f` | High | `install.log` (marker file) |\n| SHA-256 | `0190791522d2560741e67c6052fb691e01d0f3c4b8303d85219e59a4c06ebcd1` | Medium | `install.bin` |\n| SHA-256 | `beb9c5972883d92444c27ca47c0ad9c09c7ca93aebf0e7bff8cbb2f561e7b14c` | Low | `help.chm` (benign bundled help) |\n| SHA-256 | `ebfafcb27995196834aed710ce42884760abc9896db4f265815e1b93a9749ecd` | Medium | `opt.dat` |\n| SHA-256 | `8fe609eeaaea64bd6f3b5dd786be42d6ce46c41f5f7145a65932e0cab3e07b59` | High | `web.dt` (transport config — examine for C2 server) |\n| SHA-1 | `40b638c05767cc5ad9802701953efeb5315bc80f` | High | `setup.exe` (RAR SFX) |\n| SHA-1 | `3bc3eb9c78d0f867f7d138f7958c2b8854a4dc53` | High | `k.exe` (Edge-downloaded BlazingTools installer) |\n| SHA-1 | `c31bbf518e9d9bc74a6567a2e3f0c37043ad399a` | High | `perfmon-k.exe` (deleted/replaced — historical Amcache) |\n| SHA-1 | `c95f567910b56d5e1f865781582aa6c8ff9f5db9` | High | `perfmon-kconfigure.exe` (deleted — historical Amcache) |\n| Username | `shieldbase\\spsql` (SID `…-1193`) | High | Account that installed the keylogger; profile deleted post-incident |\n| Behaviour | Files in a folder where `$STANDARD_INFORMATION` is one calendar year earlier than `$FILE_NAME` (`SI<FN = True`) | Medium | Timestomp signature |\n| YARA rule | `BlazingTools_Perfect_Keylogger_Install_Log`, `BlazingTools_PKL_Filenames` | High | `/cases/Test1/analysis/yara/blazingtools_pkl.yar` |\n| Source IP (low confidence) | `172.16.6.17 (spadertech\\pman.adm)` — cross-domain IPC$ | Low | Validate with customer; possibly partner org |\n\nFull IOC register: `/cases/Test1/analysis/ioc_register.csv` (see Appendix path).\n\n---\n\n## 08 Gaps and Limitations\n\n**What is known.** The BlazingTools \"Perfect Keylogger\" install root is intact at `C:\\ProgramData\\perfmon-k\\` with all 11 components present and hashed. The install was executed on 2018-08-31 21:39:35 UTC by the deleted domain user `shieldbase\\spsql` (RID 1193) via a Microsoft Edge–downloaded installer. Anti-forensic timestomping was applied to all components, but `$FILE_NAME` timestamps preserve ground truth. An incident-response collection campaign by the `shieldbase` security team has been active against this host since at least 2020-02-22 using F-Response + Mnemosyne and (later) Velociraptor.\n\n**What is unknown.**\n\n1. **The keylogger's persistence mechanism.** None of the standard autorun locations on this host reference `perfmon-k`. The malware may have been disabled by the IR team prior to capture, or may use a non-standard ASEP (Active Setup, COM hijack, AppInit_DLLs, scheduled-task XML on disk that no longer references the path, WMI subscription).\n2. **The transport / exfiltration channel.** `web.dt` was identified as the operator-supplied configuration file but was not parsed; it likely contains an SMTP/FTP/HTTP destination plus credentials. Recommend dedicated reverse-engineering of `web.dt` and the binary parsers in `perfmon-kvw.exe`.\n3. **Identity behind `spsql`.** The user profile and NTUSER.DAT are gone. Without `shieldbase.lan` AD logs we cannot say whether `spsql` was a legitimate ex-employee whose credentials were abused, a service-account misuse, or a maliciously created domain user.\n4. **Identity behind SID `…-1212`** (added to local Administrators 2020-02-17) — most plausibly an IR account, but identity confirmation requires AD lookup.\n5. **Original C2/upload destination.** No live network connections to external IPs were captured (this is a disk image, not a memory/PCAP capture). Endpoint NetConn data is limited to `Microsoft-Windows-SMBServer/Audit` (3000) and Security EID 5140, which only show internal SMB activity.\n6. **Captured keystroke content.** `pkl.bin` (9,368 bytes) is the recorded-data store. It was not decoded; the BlazingTools data format is proprietary. Open-source `BPK-decrypter` tooling exists but is outside the scope of this triage.\n7. **The `Quarantine\\` directory at the C:\\ root.** It is empty. Whether McAfee was configured to use a different quarantine path, or whether quarantined items were manually purged, is unresolved.\n\n**What cannot be determined from available evidence.**\n\n- Whether keylogged data was successfully exfiltrated to the operator. The pkl.bin database is present but its decoded state and the network history needed to confirm transmission are not in this image.\n- Whether other hosts in `shieldbase.lan` were similarly infected. This analysis covers a single workstation only.\n\n**Evidence that would resolve the uncertainty:**\n\n- AD security log for `shieldbase.lan` covering 2018-08 (identifies spsql ownership and password-set events).\n- Edge `WebCacheV01.dat` carving for `spsql` (downloads URL of `k.exe`).\n- Decoded `pkl.bin` and `web.dt`.\n- Network/proxy logs from `172.16.5.20` (McAfee ePO) and any egress proxy.\n- Memory image of `BASE-WKSTN-01` from any of the F-Response collections.\n\n---\n\n## 09 Recommendations\n\n1. **Pivot to other hosts in `shieldbase.lan`** with a YARA sweep using the rule file at `/cases/Test1/analysis/yara/blazingtools_pkl.yar` (or the embedded filename/path/string indicators in section 07). Look specifically for `C:\\ProgramData\\perfmon-k\\*` and the SHA-256 set listed in F-01.\n2. **Audit AD for the `spsql` account** — recover when it was created, by whom, password history, and other host logons. Identify SID …-1212 as well.\n3. **Decode `pkl.bin` and `web.dt`** to recover the operator's exfiltration destination(s) and captured keystroke content.\n4. **Carve unallocated space** for the original `k.exe` download metadata in Edge `WebCacheV01.dat` and BAM/DAM ESE database.\n5. **Update the McAfee detection ruleset** — the host had an AV that did not flag this commercial keylogger. Add a custom signature using the SHA-256 set above.\n6. **Disable the local `range_admin` account** on production rebuilds (F-09).\n7. **Recover and re-image** this workstation; do not return to service. The malware files were not removed and persistence mechanism is unconfirmed.\n\n---\n\n## 10 Reproducibility Appendix\n\n- Command ledger: `/cases/Test1/logs/command_ledger.csv`\n- Mount registry: `/cases/Test1/analysis/mounts.csv`\n- Evidence inventory: `/cases/Test1/analysis/evidence_inventory.csv`\n- Parsed artefacts: `/cases/Test1/analysis/` (Amcache, MFT, UsnJrnl, Shimcache, Security/System/Application EVTX, RECmd Kroll batch)\n- YARA rules: `/cases/Test1/analysis/yara/blazingtools_pkl.yar`\n- YARA hits CSV: `/cases/Test1/exports/yara_hits.csv`\n- Helper scripts: `/cases/Test1/analysis/scripts/sec_analysis.py`, `amcache_sweep.py`, `yara_sweep.py`\n- Hive copies: `/cases/Test1/exports/hives/`, `/cases/Test1/exports/userhives/`\n- Evidence E01: `/cases/Test1/base-wkstn-01-c-drive.E01` (read-only, mounted at `/mnt/wkstn01`)\n\n**Command-ledger summary:** populated automatically by `/home/sansforensics/.claude/scripts/run_logged.sh`. See the audit summary in the closing section of the PDF.\n\n---\n\n## Confidence Level Definitions\n\n| Confidence | Definition |\n|-----------|------------|\n| Confirmed | Directly supported by raw or parsed forensic artifact. |\n| Corroborated | Supported by two or more independent artifacts. |\n| Probable | Supported by one artifact plus strong contextual evidence. |\n| Hypothesis | Plausible but not yet proven; must include the next validation step. |\n| Rejected | Tested and unsupported. |\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2431,"cache_read_input_tokens":316551,"output_tokens":18325,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2431},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[{"input_tokens":1,"output_tokens":18325,"cache_read_input_tokens":316551,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2431,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2431,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CbiY26gbSbZ8C7dhDmtdY","type":"assistant","uuid":"c5e66908-f014-43ba-ab45-c972dee0ef36","timestamp":"2026-06-04T16:33:50.299Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/cases/Test1","sessionId":"4398f556-f334-4a3b-bf73-9dbc3f3e8708","version":"2.1.136","gitBranch":"HEAD"}
