reated** on this host, added to local Administrators via GPO on 2020-02-17 |\n\n---\n\n## 04 Tools and Versions\n\n| Tool | Version | Purpose |\n|------|---------|---------|\n| libewf `ewfinfo` / `ewfverify` | 20140816 | E01 metadata, hash verification |\n| The Sleuth Kit (`fsstat`, `fls`, `icat`) | system | Volume metadata, MFT/UsnJrnl extraction |\n| EZ Tools `EvtxECmd` | 1.x | Event log → CSV |\n| EZ Tools `AmcacheParser` | 1.5.2.0 | Amcache.hve → CSV |\n| EZ Tools `AppCompatCacheParser` | 1.5.1.0 | Shimcache → CSV |\n| EZ Tools `RECmd` | 2.1.0.0 | Registry hive batch parsing (Kroll batch) |\n| EZ Tools `MFTECmd` | latest | `$MFT` and `$UsnJrnl:$J` → CSV |\n| EZ Tools `JLECmd`, `LECmd`, `SBECmd` | latest | JumpLists, LNKs, ShellBags |\n| YARA (python `yara` module) | 4.5.0 | Custom signature sweep |\n| Python 3 + custom scripts | — | Security log JSON parsing, focused IOC sweeps |\n| WeasyPrint | latest | Markdown → styled PDF rendering |\n\nAll commands routed through `/home/sansforensics/.claude/scripts/run_logged.sh` and recorded in `/cases/Test1/logs/command_ledger.csv`.\n\n---\n\n## 05 Findings\n\n### F-01 — BlazingTools \"Perfect Keylogger\" malware persistent in C:\\ProgramData\\perfmon-k\\\n\n**Confidence: Confirmed.**\n**Classification: Direct Observation (malware family named in plaintext inside `install.log`).**\n\n**Description.** A complete BlazingTools \"Perfect Keylogger\" installation is present at `C:\\ProgramData\\perfmon-k\\` (mounted at `/mnt/wkstn01/ProgramData/perfmon-k/`). The directory contains the keylogger's signature component set — `perfmon-kr.exe` (recorder), `perfmon-kvw.exe` (viewer), `perfmon-khk.dll` (keyboard-hook library), `perfmon-ki.dll`, `perfmon-kwb.dll`, plus configuration/data files `opt.dat`, `web.dt`, `pkl.bin`, `install.log`, `install.bin`, `help.chm`.\n\n**Family identification (Direct Observation).** `install.log` (520 bytes) contains the UTF-16LE marker string **`BlazingTools Perfect Keylogger`** alongside the install path **`C:\\ProgramData\\perfmon-k`**. The YARA rule shipped with this case (`/cases/Test1/analysis/yara/blazingtools_pkl.yar`) matches `install.log` on rule `BlazingTools_Perfect_Keylogger_Install_Log`. BlazingTools \"Perfect Keylogger\" is a commercial keystroke-logger / spyware family that records keystrokes, captures screenshots, hooks browser form fields, and uploads collected data over SMTP/FTP/HTTP per the operator-defined `web.dt` configuration.\n\n**On-disk component table.**\n\n| File Path | Size Bytes | SHA-256 | Evidence Source | Notes |\n|-----------|------------|---------|-----------------|-------|\n| `C:\\ProgramData\\perfmon-k\\help.chm` | 407,279 | `beb9c5972883d92444c27ca47c0ad9c09c7ca93aebf0e7bff8cbb2f561e7b14c` | EVID-001 | Help/marketing file bundled with installer |\n| `C:\\ProgramData\\perfmon-k\\install.bin` | 83,456 | `0190791522d2560741e67c6052fb691e01d0f3c4b8303d85219e59a4c06ebcd1` | EVID-001 | Installer payload binary |\n| `C:\\ProgramData\\perfmon-k\\install.log` | 520 | `4b64135662977d806f8d12067815848827cd977c3696a60c30d85a157f6b945f` | EVID-001 | **Contains \"BlazingTools Perfect Keylogger\" plaintext** |\n| `C:\\ProgramData\\perfmon-k\\opt.dat` | 64 | `ebfafcb27995196834aed710ce42884760abc9896db4f265815e1b93a9749ecd` | EVID-001 | Options binary |\n| `C:\\ProgramData\\perfmon-k\\perfmon-khk.dll` | 1,307,648 | `225efff946151edeb6f860f5e4d68aa7025ca7abef67ddb215f5c89445d3356c` | EVID-001 | Keyboard-hook DLL |\n| `C:\\ProgramData\\perfmon-k\\perfmon-ki.dll` | 275,968 | `fa76d9059fc4fe103e3de1868c76d86efbac9295fcd3e5f1c430cd1c5b4ad710` | EVID-001 | Injection helper DLL |\n| `C:\\ProgramData\\perfmon-k\\perfmon-kr.exe` | 1,352,704 | `fc7f5094bc182a05e782e0b775eccab9e662a3d207e89ab7f075db18a4c19c75` | EVID-001 | Recorder executable |\n| `C:\\ProgramData\\perfmon-k\\perfmon-kvw.exe` | 1,570,816 | `128cdb7c58bfda11a88c21e41e48df47f2122a1761d69aec5af79e241a712185` | EVID-001 | Viewer/admin console executable |\n| `C:\\ProgramData\\perfmon-k\\perfmon-kwb.dll` | 1,348,608 | `8db5e3bdd57ed77f80e1dbd5f11a48a19f69faa2281f1039b615ee8b4a09407c` | EVID-001 | Browser-hook DLL |\n| `C:\\ProgramData\\perfmon-k\\pkl.bin` | 9,368 | `5f7925d5e11232a4391daabd56559ad79e662d03e9d6f791b4ace3ec3142a78b` | EVID-001 | Collected-data database (`pkl` = Perfect Keylogger) |\n| `C:\\ProgramData\\perfmon-k\\web.dt` | 304 | `8fe609eeaaea64bd6f3b5dd786be42d6ce46c41f5f7145a65932e0cab3e07b59` | EVID-001 | Upload/transport configuration |\n\n**Timestomp evidence (Direct Observation; Corroborated by MFT FN vs SI comparison).** Every file in the keylogger directory has `$STANDARD_INFORMATION` timestamps set to **2017-08-31** but `$FILE_NAME` (FN) timestamps set to **2018-08-31**. `MFTECmd` marked the comparison flag `SI<FN = True` for all rows. Representative entries (UTC):\n\n| File | SI Created (`$10`) | FN Created (`$30`) — real | MFT entry |\n|------|--------------------|---------------------------|-----------|\n| `help.chm` | 2017-08-31 17:30:35.960 | **2018-08-31 21:39:35.960** | 148033 |\n| `install.bin` | 2017-08-31 17:30:35.960 | **2018-08-31 21:39:35.960** | 148034 |\n| `install.log` | 2017-08-31 17:30:50.444 | **2018-08-31 21:39:50.444** | 148050 |\n| `perfmon-khk.dll` | 2017-08-31 17:30:35.975 | **2018-08-31 21:39:35.975** | 148036 |\n| `perfmon-ki.dll` | 2017-08-31 17:30:35.991 | **2018-08-31 21:39:35.991** | 148042 |\n| `perfmon-kr.exe` | 2017-08-31 17:30:35.991 | **2018-08-31 21:39:35.991** | 148043 |\n| `perfmon-kvw.exe` | 2017-08-31 17:30:35.991 | **2018-08-31 21:39:35.991** | 148040 |\n| `perfmon-kwb.dll` | 2017-08-31 17:30:35.991 | **2018-08-31 21:39:35.991** | 148041 |\n| `pkl.bin` | 2017-08-31 17:39:19.163 | **2018-08-31 21:42:43.231** | 3134 |\n| `web.dt` | 2017-08-31 17:33:47.983 | **2018-08-31 21:42:47.980** | 120226 |\n| `opt.dat` | 2017-08-31 17:39:03.998 | **2018-08-31 21:48:03.999** | 120972 |\n\nThe hour-of-day delta (≈+4h) and the exact one-year date shift indicate the operator used a tool such as `SetMACE`, `timestomp.exe`, or a PowerShell time-stomping script to forge the SI timestamps. The FN timestamps cannot be modified via standard Windows APIs and therefore retain the true creation times.\n\nParent directory `.\\ProgramData\\perfmon-k` is MFT entry 148032, ParentSequenceNumber 3 — also stamped to 2017-08-31 in SI.\n\n**Persistence (Hypothesis).** No keylogger entry was identified in:\n\n- `HKLM\\Software\\Microsoft\\Windows\\CurrentVersion\\Run` (only `SecurityHealth`, `VMware User Process`)\n- `HKLM\\Software\\Wow6432Node\\Microsoft\\Windows\\CurrentVersion\\Run` (only `GrooveMonitor`, `McAfeeUpdaterUI`, `ShStatEXE`, `TeamsMachineInstaller`)\n- `HKCU\\Software\\Microsoft\\Windows\\CurrentVersion\\Run` for `mhill` (only `OneDrive`, `com.squirrel.Teams.Teams`)\n- `HKLM\\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services` (no `perfmon-k`, no `BlazingTools`)\n- `Microsoft-Windows-TaskScheduler/Operational` (no perfmon-k task)\n- `C:\\Windows\\System32\\Tasks\\` (no perfmon-k task)\n\nThe keylogger may have run only on-demand at the time of operator-initiated activity, used a less common autostart extension point (e.g. `Active Setup`, image-file-execution-options hijack, COM hijack, AppInit_DLLs), or been disabled after the IR team gained visibility in early 2020 but left in place for forensic preservation. **Further validation required.**\n\n**Detection by McAfee VirusScan: Negative (Direct Observation).** `McShield.evtx` is present on disk (69,632 bytes) but contains **0 event records** — confirmed by `EvtxECmd` (\"Total event log records found: 0\"). `C:\\Quarantine\\` is empty. McAfee VirusScan was active during the install window (the McAfee Agent / On-Access Scanner services have multiple start events in `System.evtx`), so the malware either signature-evaded the 2018-vintage definitions or McAfee logging was rolled over.\n\n**Alternative explanations considered.**\n\n1. *Legitimate \"PerfMon K-edition\" performance tool.* **Rejected.** No vendor by that name exists; the directory contains the literal `BlazingTools Perfect Keylogger` string in `install.log`; the file naming pattern (`-kr`/`-kvw`/`-khk`/`-ki`/`-kwb` + `pkl.bin` + `opt.dat`/`web.dt`) exactly matches the published PKL component layout.\n2. *Planted by the IR team for safe analysis after the original host was already compromised.* Not impossible but unsupported — the IR collection timeline begins on 2020-02-22, eighteen months *after* the keylogger files were created. The drop chain (Microsoft Edge → user Temp → ProgramData) is also inconsistent with intentional IR placement, which would typically use `C:\\Tools\\` or an analyst share.\n3. *Test artefact from a prior compliance exercise.* Possible but unsupported by any documentation present on the host. The `Kansa` PowerShell IR script-block events observed two weeks earlier (2018-08-15) would have captured installed software inventory; whether they recorded `C:\\ProgramData\\perfmon-k` is outside this analysis scope (the collected Kansa output would be on the analyst workstation, not the target).\n\n**Limitation.** Binary string-analysis of the executables was not productive — `perfmon-kr.exe` strings are largely encrypted/packed and the `BlazingTools` plaintext only appears in the install log. The encrypted layout is consistent with the commercial PKL installer's anti-analysis routines. Independent hash submission to VirusTotal (offline in this engagement) would corroborate family identification.\n\n**Tool output paths.**\n\n- `/cases/Test1/analysis/mft.csv` (lines for MFT entries 3134, 120226, 120972, 148032, 148033, 148034, 148036, 148040, 148041, 148042, 148043, 148050)\n- `/cases/Test1/analysis/amcache_UnassociatedFileEntries.csv` (rows for `setup.exe`, `k.exe`, `perfmon-k.exe`, `perfmon-kconfigure.exe`)\n- `/cases/Test1/analysis/yara/blazingtools_pkl.yar`\n- `/cases/Test1/exports/yara_hits.csv`\n- `/cases/Test1/logs/20260604T161739Z_10110_stdout.log` (SHA-256 hashes of all components)\n\n---\n\n### F-02 — Deployment chain: shieldbase\\spsql downloaded the installer via Microsoft Edge\n\n**Confidence: Corroborated (Amcache + scheduled-task SID + MFT FN timestamps).**\n**Classification: Supported Inference.**\n\nThe Amcache hive contains three execution-touchpoint records under the `spsql` user profile, all on **2018-08-31**:\n\n| Amcache key-LWT (UTC) | File | SHA1 | Path | Size |\n|-----------------------|------|------|------|------|\n| 21:14:30 | `onedrivesetup.exe` | `3284ac8d523ea063014ca7c46d90c05d70c0dda8` | `C:\\Users\\spsql\\AppData\\Local\\Microsoft\\OneDrive\\update\\onedrivesetup.exe` | 26.4 MB (Microsoft signed; benign, first-run OneDrive provisioning) |\n| 21:38:29 | `setup.exe` | `40b638c05767cc5ad9802701953efeb5315bc80f` | `C:\\Users\\spsql\\AppData\\Local\\Temp\\rarsfx0\\setup.exe` | 1.36 MB (WinRAR self-extracting stub; LinkDate 2018-08-11) |\n| 21:39:54 | **`k.exe`** | `3bc3eb9c78d0f867f7d138f7958c2b8854a4dc53` | **`C:\\Users\\spsql\\AppData\\Local\\Packages\\Microsoft.MicrosoftEdge_8wekyb3d8bbwe\\TempState\\Downloads\\k.exe`** | **14.02 MB** (LinkDate `2010-02-10` — fake/backdated) |\n\nTwo further entries record the actual deployment:\n\n| Amcache key-LWT (UTC) | File | SHA1 | Path |\n|-----------------------|------|------|------|\n| 21:43:21 | `perfmon-k.exe` | `c31bbf518e9d9bc74a6567a2e3f0c37043ad399a` | `C:\\ProgramData\\perfmon-k\\perfmon-k.exe` (file no longer present; replaced by the `-kr`/`-kvw` set) |\n| 21:48:03 | `perfmon-kconfigure.exe` | `c95f567910b56d5e1f865781582aa6c8ff9f5db9` | `C:\\ProgramData\\perfmon-k\\perfmon-kconfigure.exe` (no longer present) |\n\n**Supporting Inference: Deployment narrative.** User `shieldbase\\spsql` downloaded the 14 MB BlazingTools installer (`k.exe`) via the Microsoft Edge legacy browser (file landed in Edge's UWP package TempState/Downloads). They executed `k.exe`; the BlazingTools installer extracted an embedded WinRAR SFX into `%LOCALAPPDATA%\\Temp\\rarsfx0\\setup.exe`, which then dropped the persistent components into `C:\\ProgramData\\perfmon-k\\` (FN timestamps 21:39:35). A configuration phase followed (21:42:43–21:48:03) writing `pkl.bin`, `web.dt`, `opt.dat`, and finally invoking `perfmon-kconfigure.exe` (21:48:03). The total install window is **~10 minutes (21:38:29 → 21:48:03 UTC, 31 Aug 2018)**.\n\n**The spsql account has been deleted from this host** — there is no `C:\\Users\\spsql` directory, no SAM entry (it was a domain account anyway), and the registry `ProfileList` does not contain RID 1193. The only surviving reference is `C:\\Windows\\System32\\Tasks\\OneDrive Standalone Update Task-S-1-5-21-3445421715-2530590580-3149308974-1193`, file-system-dated **2018-08-31** (the same day as the keylogger install) — consistent with OneDrive provisioning its per-user update task during the user's first-run flow at 21:14 UTC. This task file was not garbage-collected when the profile was removed and therefore preserves the SID-to-presence binding.\n\n**Alternative explanation considered.** The SHA1 `40b638c0…` for `setup.exe` could theoretically come from a benign WinRAR stub for unrelated software; however the immediate co-location with `k.exe` in Edge downloads, the matching execution window, and the destination directory's confirmed BlazingTools content together rule out an unrelated archive.\n\n**Limitation.** The Edge UWP profile data for `spsql` is no longer recoverable from the live filesystem because the user profile was removed; `$UsnJrnl:$J` retention had also rolled over by 2021-09-16 (no journal records reference `spsql`, `perfmon-k`, or `rarsfx0`). The download URL therefore cannot be recovered from this image without carving the BAM/DAM database or the deleted ESE WebCache. Validation step: carve unallocated clusters around MFT 3134/148032 for the original Edge `WebCacheV01.dat` or BAM/DAM database fragments referring to spsql's SID `…-1193`.\n\n---\n\n### F-03 — Anti-forensic tradecraft\n\n**Confidence: Confirmed.**\n**Classification: Direct Observation.**\n\nThree anti-forensic behaviours were observed:\n\n1. **Timestomping** of every file in `C:\\ProgramData\\perfmon-k\\` — SI timestamps backdated exactly one year (see F-01 table). FN timestamps preserve the true 2018-08-31 install times.\n2. **User-profile removal** for `spsql` (RID 1193) — eliminates user-attributable artefacts such as NTUSER.DAT, browser history, RecentDocs, ShellBags, and JumpLists. The OneDrive scheduled-task file is the only artefact that survived the cleanup.\n3. **Fake LinkDate on `k.exe`** — the downloaded installer reports an executable LinkDate of `2010-02-10 13:09:37`, twelve years older than its observed first-execution time, consistent with PE timestamp forgery (also a common BlazingTools commercial-build practice).\n\n**Alternative explanation.** Some PE compilers (older Borland, packed Themida builds) emit non-standard LinkDate values; LinkDate alone is weak evidence. Treated as supporting circumstantial evidence only.\n\n---\n\n### F-04 — Local-administrators escalation (likely IR provisioning, not malicious)\n\n**Confidence: Probable (legitimate IR provisioning).**\n**Classification: Supported Inference.**\n\nEID **4732** (\"A member was added to a security-enabled local group\") fired exactly **once** in the entire ~3.5-year Security log:\n\n| TimeCreated UTC | Subject | Target group | Member added |\n|-----------------|---------|--------------|--------------|\n| 2020-02-17 08:00:37.430 | `shieldbase\\BASE-WKSTN-01$` (SYSTEM, SubjectLogonId `0x3E7`) | `Builtin\\Administrators` (`S-1-5-32-544`) | `S-1-5-21-3445421715-2530590580-3149308974-1212` |\n\nThe subject is the computer's own machine account (`BASE-WKSTN-01$`) running as SYSTEM — the classic fingerprint of a **Group Policy Restricted-Groups** policy push from `shieldbase.lan` Active Directory.\n\nFive days later (2020-02-22 23:16) the **first** F-Response Subject service install on this host was executed by `shieldbase\\cbarton-a` (see F-05). The temporal proximity (5 days), the lack of any other 4732 events in the log, and the absence of an interactive logon by SID …-1212 on this workstation are all consistent with the **IR/threat-hunting team adding a managed admin account to this host via GPO** in order to authenticate F-Response collections. The identity of SID …-1212 cannot be resolved from this single workstation's hives because no profile was ever materialised; resolution requires querying `shieldbase.lan` AD directly.\n\n**Alternative explanation considered.** An attacker exploiting GPO write access could equally fire a 4732 with SYSTEM context. The non-malicious interpretation is stronger here because (a) only one such event exists in the whole log, (b) it precedes a documented IR-collection campaign by a small interval, and (c) the IR-team account `cbarton-a` is observed performing F-Response activity shortly after.\n\n---\n\n### F-05 — Documented Incident Response collection activity (2020-02 → 2021-09)\n\n**Confidence: Confirmed.**\n**Classification: Direct Observation (Security log 4697 + System log 7045).**\n\n| First observed UTC | Service installed | ImagePath | Installer subject |\n|--------------------|-------------------|-----------|-------------------|\n| 2019-11-13 02:53:48 | `mnemosyne` | `C:\\windows/Mnemosyne.sys` (note the forward-slash — characteristic of F-Response Mnemosyne) | `shieldbase\\BASE-WKSTN-01$` (SYSTEM — installer ran as SYSTEM) |\n| 2020-02-22 23:16:16 | `F-Response Subject` | `C:\\windows\\subject_srv.exe -s \\` | **`shieldbase\\cbarton-a`** |\n| 2019-12-24 03:43:30 | `Sysmon64` / `SysmonDrv` | `C:\\WINDOWS\\Sysmon64.exe`, `C:\\WINDOWS\\SysmonDrv.sys` | `shieldbase\\BASE-WKSTN-01$` |\n| 2020-02-27 20:04:23 | `Velociraptor Service` | (per System EID 7045) | `shieldbase\\BASE-WKSTN-01$` |\n\nThe F-Response Subject service was re-installed at least **4 times** by `cbarton-a` and the Mnemosyne kernel driver service was re-installed/restarted **19 times** between 2018-09 and 2021-09. The final pair of installs/starts immediately precedes the disk capture:\n\n- 2021-09-16 02:52:10 — `mnemosyne` demand start\n- 2021-09-16 03:01:57 — `F-Response Subject` auto start\n- 2021-09-16 03:01:59 — `mnemosyne` demand start\n- 2021-09-16 03:10:21 — **acquisition timestamp from `ewfinfo`**\n\nThis is consistent with the disk image having been captured remotely *over* F-Response.\n\nNetwork share access (Security EID 5140) confirms the IR access pattern:\n\n| Hits | Share | User | From IP |\n|------|-------|------|---------|\n| 14,250 | `*\\IPC$` | `NT AUTHORITY\\ANONYMOUS LOGON` | 172.16.7.13 |\n| 2,641 | `*\\IPC$` | `NT AUTHORITY\\ANONYMOUS LOGON` | 172.16.7.14 |\n| 65 | `*\\IPC$` | `shieldbase\\cbarton-a` | 172.16.5.25 |\n| 15 | `*\\IPC$` | `shieldbase\\rsydow-a` | 172.16.4.4 |\n| 8 | `*\\C$` | `shieldbase\\rsydow-a` | 172.16.4.4 |\n| 8 | `*\\TempFRes` | `shieldbase\\cbarton-a` | 172.16.5.25 |\n| 7 | `*\\C$` | `shieldbase\\BASE-HUNT-03$` | 172.16.5.28 |\n| 4 | `*\\ADMIN$` | `shieldbase\\cbarton-a` | 172.16.5.25 |\n| 2 | `*\\IPC$` | `spadertech\\pman.adm` | 172.16.6.17 |\n| 1 | `*\\ADMIN$` | `shieldbase\\BASE-HUNT-02$` | 172.16.5.27 |\n\n`TempFRes` is the temporary share F-Response creates during forensic collection. The `BASE-HUNT-02` and `BASE-HUNT-03` computer accounts performing C$/ADMIN$ access strongly support legitimate threat-hunting workstations.\n\n**Cross-domain access from `spadertech\\pman.adm` (172.16.6.17) — limited.** Two IPC$ hits over the entire log range. This is the only non-`shieldbase` user observed accessing the host. The `pman.adm` naming convention (admin suffix) and the small hit count are consistent with a partner-org / managed-services account performing diagnostic checks, but the source domain (`spadertech`) is not the host's domain and warrants verification by the customer.\n\n**Limitation.** The IR team's specific findings, ticket history, and chain-of-custody for the keylogger artefact are external to this image and are not represented in the on-host telemetry beyond service installs and share access.\n\n---\n\n### F-06 — Kansa PowerShell IR collection (2018-08-15, ~2 weeks pre-incident)\n\n**Confidence: Confirmed.**\n**Classification: Direct Observation (PowerShell EID 4104 script-block logging).**\n\n`Microsoft-Windows-PowerShell/Operational` contains **1,218** EID-4104 (script-block logging) events. Sampled blocks contain Kansa module signatures including `Get-Tasklistv.ps1`, `Get-ProcsWMI.ps1`, and the comment header `Kansa.ps1 output directive follows`, all timestamped 2018-08-15. Kansa is a SANS-published PowerShell-based incident-response acquisition framework (`https://github.com/davehull/Kansa`). The collection ran approximately **16 days before** the keylogger was installed (2018-08-31). The Kansa run does **not** indicate an active compromise at that point; rather it appears to be a baseline / proactive sweep.\n\n**Limitation.** Kansa collection output is written to the analyst's machine, not the target, so on this image we only see the script-block log evidence that Kansa was *executed*, not what it returned.\n\n---\n\n### F-07 — High-volume WinRM activity is Windows Event Forwarding, not malicious\n\n**Confidence: Confirmed.**\n**Classification: Direct Observation.**\n\n`Microsoft-Windows-WinRM/Operational` accounts for the bulk of the captured event volume:\n\n- EID 132 — 233,833 events\n- EID 145 — 210,037 events (of which 209,791 enumerate `http://schemas.microsoft.com/wbem/wsman/1/SubscriptionManager/Subscription`)\n- EID 254 — 46,355 events\n- EID 138/142/161 — ~23k each\n\nA 1m25s heartbeat cadence is observed (e.g., `2021-08-12 16:23:55 → 16:25:20 → 16:26:45 …`). This is the characteristic poll cadence of a Windows Event Forwarder pulling a Subscription Manager URL. **It is benign.**\n\n---\n\n### F-08 — McAfee VirusScan failed to detect the keylogger\n\n**Confidence: Confirmed.**\n**Classification: Direct Observation.**\n\n`McShield.evtx` contains 0 records. `C:\\Quarantine\\` contains 0 files. McAfee Agent + VirusScan Enterprise 8.8 + Host Intrusion Prevention services are all present and started repeatedly in the System log. No AV alert for the BlazingTools components is present in `Application.evtx`. **The keylogger evaded the installed AV solution throughout the 3+ years it lived on disk.**\n\n---\n\n### F-09 — `range_admin` local account\n\n**Confidence: Probable (lab/training environment artefact).**\n**Classification: Supported Inference.**\n\nSAM contains the local account `range_admin` (RID 1003, Administrators-group member, created 2018-05-04, password set 2018-08-29, **0 successful logons**, account enabled). The \"range\" naming convention is consistent with a cyber-range / training environment baseline account and is not, by itself, evidence of compromise. Worth flagging because (a) it is in the local `Administrators` group, (b) the password was changed only two days before the spsql user's keylogger installation, and (c) the account has zero recorded interactive logons across the entire 3.5-year log. Recommend disabling on a production rebuild.\n\n---\n\n## 06 Activity Timeline\n\n| UTC | Event | Evidence |\n|-----|-------|----------|\n| 2018-05-04 18:14 | Earliest event in this dataset — Windows 10 1709 install / domain join | `evtx_all.csv` MIN(TimeCreated) |\n| 2018-05-09 02:54 | Built-in `Administrator` last interactive logon | SAM RID 500 LastLoginTime |\n| 2018-05-10 → 2018-05-14 | McAfee VirusScan / HIPS / Agent services installed | System EID 7045 |\n| 2018-08-15 15:32 | `cbarton-a` profile first created on host | ProfileList ProfileLoadTime |\n| 2018-08-15 ≈16:30 | **Kansa IR PowerShell collection executed** (1,218 4104 script-blocks) | PowerShell/Operational EID 4104 |\n| 2018-08-29 02:57 | `range_admin` local account password set | SAM RID 1003 LastPasswordChange |\n| 2018-08-31 21:14:30 | `spsql` OneDrive setup runs (first-run) | Amcache `onedrivesetup.exe` |\n| **2018-08-31 21:38:29** | **`spsql` executes WinRAR 